  "signature": "ed25519:b1c2d3e4f5a6b7c8d9e0f1a2b3c4d5e6f7a8b9c0d1e2f3a4b5c6d7e8f9a0b1c2",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-sqa",
      "rationale": "The FEA ensemble (Ansys 2022 R2, FDA in-house solver) is subject to documented software quality assurance procedures including version control, regression test suites, and configuration management records consistent with FDA software guidance. Ansys commercial solver holds ISO 9001 certification. FDA in-house code is managed under a documented SQA plan with traceability to requirements. Achieves Gradation 2 (commercial software with documented SQA), meeting the required level for MRL 3 / Medium consequence."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-ncv",
      "rationale": "Numerical code verification was performed via comparison of FEA predictions against closed-form analytical solutions for beam bending and contact mechanics benchmarks. Patch tests for element formulations were passed. Both solvers reproduced reference solutions within 0.5% for all benchmark cases. This satisfies Gradation 2 requirements: solution verification against known analytical benchmarks with documented pass criteria."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-discretization",
      "rationale": "A systematic mesh convergence study was conducted using three mesh densities (coarse ~85k elements, medium ~210k elements, fine ~520k elements). Richardson extrapolation was applied to estimate the grid convergence index (GCI) for each QoI. GCI values were below 1.2% for stiffness, 1.8% for yield force, and 2.1% for force at 40 mm displacement. The production mesh (medium density) was selected based on convergence and computational efficiency. Exceeds Gradation 2 by providing quantified GCI estimates; achieves Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-solver-error",
      "rationale": "Iterative solver convergence was monitored via residual norms; all simulations converged to residual tolerance below 1e-6 for force and displacement. Contact algorithm convergence was verified by checking penetration norms and contact force equilibrium at each load step. No non-convergence events were recorded across the 11-construct ensemble. Satisfies Gradation 2: documented convergence criteria with verification that criteria were met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-use-error",
      "rationale": "Model setup was performed by two independent analysts following a documented simulation protocol. A peer review checklist covering boundary conditions, material assignments, contact definitions, and load application was completed and signed for each simulation run. Discrepancies between analysts were resolved prior to final submission. This dual-analyst review process satisfies Gradation 2 for use error control."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-model-form",
      "rationale": "The continuum FEA model employs nonlinear isotropic elastic-plastic constitutive behavior for Ti-6Al-4V (ASTM F136) with material parameters derived from coupon tensile testing of the same material lot as the test constructs. Frictional contact (Coulomb, mu=0.2) is applied at screw-vertebral body block interfaces. Geometric nonlinearity is enabled to capture large-displacement response under compression-bending loading. Model form choices are justified by literature precedent and sensitivity analyses demonstrating that alternative contact formulations and friction coefficients within plausible ranges alter QoIs by less than 3%. Achieves Gradation 3: model form is justified with documented sensitivity analysis."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-model-inputs",
      "rationale": "Material properties (elastic modulus, yield strength, tangent modulus) were measured from five tensile coupons machined from the same Ti-6Al-4V bar stock used to manufacture test constructs. Geometric dimensions were measured via coordinate measuring machine (CMM) on three representative screws and rods. Uncertainty in material inputs was propagated through the model using a one-at-a-time sensitivity study; combined input uncertainty contributes less than 4% to QoI variance. Satisfies Gradation 3: input parameters characterized from direct measurement with quantified uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-test-samples",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were assembled and tested: six at Laboratory A (FDA) and five at Laboratory B (independent contract lab). All constructs were assembled from the same production lot of screws and rods. Sample traceability records (lot numbers, assembly torque logs) are archived. Inter-laboratory variability was assessed; coefficient of variation for stiffness was 4.2%, consistent with expected manufacturing variability. Achieves Gradation 3: multi-laboratory sample set with documented traceability and inter-lab variability characterization."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-test-conditions",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single load configuration (ASTM F1717 standard compression-bending at 5 mm/min crosshead rate, ambient temperature 23±2°C, standard UHMWPE vertebral body blocks). Only one test condition was evaluated; no variation in loading rate, temperature, or block material was explored. This limits the factor to Gradation 2 (single well-characterized test condition per standard protocol), which is below the required Gradation 3. This known gap is documented and accepted by the credibility assessment team as the standard F1717 protocol is the regulatory reference condition and additional conditions are outside the COU scope."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-equivalency",
      "rationale": "FEA model inputs were mapped directly from measured experimental parameters: CMM-measured screw geometry was used to generate CAD geometry for meshing; tensile coupon data from the same material lot informed constitutive parameters; assembly torque was converted to preload via a calibrated torque-preload relationship validated separately. A formal equivalency table was prepared documenting each experimental parameter and its corresponding model input, with traceability references. Achieves Gradation 3: documented parameter equivalency with traceable mapping from experiment to model."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-output-comparison",
      "rationale": "Quantitative comparison was performed using the ASME V&V 40 validation metric E/uval for each QoI. Validation uncertainty (uval) was computed as the root-sum-square of experimental measurement uncertainty, input parameter uncertainty, and numerical solution uncertainty. E/uval values were 0.84 (stiffness), 1.21 (yield force), and 1.43 (force at 40 mm), all below the pre-specified threshold of 1.96. Percentage differences were 3.1%, 6.7%, and 8.4%, all below the 10% acceptance bound. Achieves Gradation 3: quantitative metric with combined uncertainty quantification applied to all three QoIs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-qoi-relevance",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are directly specified in ASTM F1717 as the regulatory endpoints for spinal implant mechanical performance assessment. They are mechanistically linked to clinical failure modes: stiffness governs load sharing with the spine; yield force is the onset of permanent deformation; force at 40 mm characterizes post-yield energy absorption. The mapping from QoI to clinical consequence was reviewed and approved by the clinical subject matter expert on the assessment team. Achieves Gradation 3: QoIs are the regulatory standard endpoints with documented clinical relevance mapping."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-validation-relevance",
      "rationale": "The validation activity directly replicates the COU: the same non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw geometry, same Ti-6Al-4V material, same ASTM F1717 test configuration, and same FEA modeling framework are used in both validation and the intended regulatory submission context. No extrapolation of geometry, material, or loading regime is required. The validation domain fully encompasses the COU domain for all three QoIs. Achieves Gradation 3: validation activities are directly coincident with the COU with no extrapolation required."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-noncannulated-decision",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment team reviewed all 13 V&V 40 factors for the non-cannulated pedicle screw compression-bending FEA model (COU1). Twelve of thirteen factors meet or exceed their required credibility levels. The single exception — Test conditions (achieved Gradation 2 vs. required Gradation 3) — is accepted because ASTM F1717 defines a single standardized test condition as the regulatory reference, and the COU explicitly limits model use to that condition; no extrapolation to other conditions is claimed. Quantitative validation metrics (E/uval < 1.96 and percentage difference < 10%) were satisfied for all three QoIs across the 11-construct, two-laboratory experimental dataset. Input parameter traceability from material coupon testing and CMM measurement to model inputs is complete. Software quality assurance, numerical verification, and convergence documentation are in place for both solvers in the ensemble. The provenance chain from raw experimental data through uncertainty quantification to the final validation metric is fully documented and archived. On this basis, the assessment team concludes that the FEA modeling framework has sufficient credibility to support the intended regulatory decision for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw design under ASTM F1717 static compression-bending loading. Decision: Accepted.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
